At first, find out what variables are correlated to BMI.

dat <- read.delim("survey.csv",sep=",",header=FALSE)[1:70,]
height <- dat[28,-1]
height <- as.numeric(as.character(unlist(height)))/100

#still have one invalid value of height, use average height instead
#sum(height)/70
heights <- height*height

weight <- dat[53,-1]
weight <- as.numeric(as.character(unlist(weight)))

BMI <- weight/heights

ProExp <- dat[1,-1]
ProExp <- as.numeric(as.character(unlist(ProExp)))

happy <- dat[52,-1]
happy <- as.numeric(as.character(unlist(happy)))

sleep <- dat[56,-1]
sleep <- as.numeric(as.character(unlist(sleep)))

livefromwork <- dat[57,-1]
livefromwork <- as.numeric(as.character((unlist(livefromwork))))

coffee <- dat[68,-1]
coffee <- as.numeric(as.character(unlist(coffee)))

chocolate <- dat[36,-1]
chocolate <- as.numeric(as.character(unlist(chocolate)))

mat <- cbind(ProExp,happy,sleep,livefromwork,coffee,chocolate)
cor(BMI,mat)
##       ProExp     happy      sleep livefromwork    coffee  chocolate
## [1,] 0.35049 0.1048881 -0.2746728    0.1658858 0.4348902 0.07075284

The result shows that BMI has some relationship with professional years, sleep time and coffee.

for(i in 1:71){
  if(chocoBMI[2,i]==1){
    like <- c(like,chocoBMI[1,i])
  }
  else
    dislike <- c(dislike,chocoBMI[1,i])
}
length(like)

Find the relationship between BMI and sleep time. Using regression.

library(boot)
x <- sleep
y <- BMI

plot(x,y)

x.plot = seq(min(x),max(x), length.out = 1000)

#linear model
#Degree 1
lm1 = lm(y~x)
summary(lm1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max

## 
## Coefficients:

## x            -1.2725     0.5363  -2.373   0.0204 *
